{
  "result": "At dawn, the city pretends to be gentle. Delivery trucks whisper down wet streets, and the bakery on the corner exhales a warm, yeasty promise into the cold air. I like to walk before everyone remembers who they are. In that blue hour, office towers are only glass cliffs, pigeons are philosophers, and the river moves like an unread sentence.\n\nThere is a bench beside the tram stop where an old man feeds sparrows with unreasonable patience. He breaks each crust into equal pieces, as if fairness could be practiced into existence one bird at a time. Some mornings we nod; some mornings we don't. Still, his ritual steadies me. It says: begin small, begin again.\n\nBy noon the spell is broken. Screens bloom, sirens ricochet, people speed past carrying plans that barely fit in their hands. Yet even then, tiny miracles survive. A mechanic sings opera while changing tires. A child in a dinosaur coat salutes every bus. A barista draws a fern in my coffee and, for ten seconds, I believe in elegance.\n\nAt night, windows light up like separate planets. Somewhere, someone laughs too loudly. Somewhere else, someone cries into dishwater. The moon hangs over all of it, indifferent and faithful. I go home, set my keys on the table, and think how strange it is that a day can be ordinary and sacred at once. Tomorrow will look similar, I know, but similarity is not sameness; each sunrise edits the script and leaves room for surprise.",
